{
  "stem": "3964.1",
  "chunk_idx": 1,
  "model": "openai/gpt-oss-120b",
  "elapsed_s": 10.0,
  "sentences_input": [
    {
      "segment_idx": 0,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 21,
      "text": "And as far as I can remember, we always had a wonderful, warm relationship.",
      "word_count": 14
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 0,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 22,
      "text": "Our family was a fairly orthodox family, orthodox Jewish family.",
      "word_count": 10
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 0,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 23,
      "text": "We used to go to minyan every day.",
      "word_count": 8
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 0,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 24,
      "text": "Although the town itself had only 16 Jewish families, nevertheless it was a cohesive [PAUSES FOR 3 SECONDS] group of people living in that town.",
      "word_count": 25
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 0,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 25,
      "text": "And we really were family with everybody else.",
      "word_count": 8
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 0,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 26,
      "text": "Things changed, of course, as time went on in 1932 and 1933.",
      "word_count": 12
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 0,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 27,
      "text": "Hitler was elected, or put into power.",
      "word_count": 7
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 0,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 28,
      "text": "And for what reason I really don't know and I haven't really explored it and looked into it, Gemunden and the whole general area where I lived became extremely Nazified, if, if that's a word.",
      "word_count": 35
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 0,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 29,
      "text": "There was lots of unemployment.",
      "word_count": 5
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 0,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 30,
      "text": "But in any event, people in Gemunden, in my town, those who had been friends with us and our family, suddenly because they were promised, I guess, a better life from Nazi officials became our enemies.",
      "word_count": 36
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 0,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 31,
      "text": "I remember back in 1933 and 1934 when the first boycotts took place in Gemunden, when the brown shirts, or SA, were standing in front of our house, posters put on our windows and doors-- don't buy by Jews, don't patronize Jews.",
      "word_count": 42
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 0,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 32,
      "text": "It was a very-- it was a terrible experience for me, because that was the first time I felt being persecuted.",
      "word_count": 21
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 0,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 33,
      "text": "I always knew I was a Jew, obviously, because the rest of the community was Christian.",
      "word_count": 16
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 0,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 34,
      "text": "But I never really knew I was any different from the Christians other than I was Jewish.",
      "word_count": 17
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 0,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 35,
      "text": "And all of sudden I was an outcast.",
      "word_count": 8
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 0,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 36,
      "text": "In 1932, I started going to school-- 1931, excuse me. 1931, I started going to school.",
      "word_count": 16
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 0,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 37,
      "text": "And that was German public school.",
      "word_count": 6
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 0,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 38,
      "text": "Things were fairly decent yet in those days.",
      "word_count": 8
    }
  ],
